stylometry:
The total cost of managing a product in inventory is the sum of annual carrying costs and annual ordering costs. These costs are determined by developing an EOQ model. Annual carrying costs is the quantity of inventory divided by 2 multiplied by the cost of holding per year. Annual ordering costs is the annual demand divided by order size which is then multiplied by cost per order. The costs we are trying to balance are these costs (ordering and carrying).
The less inventory we order at a time results in less carrying costs, but we have to order more frequently which increases ordering costs.
The more inventory we order at a time results in less ordering costs, but more carrying costs.
What we need to do is to find the balance of ordering inventory that will result in a minimun of the total cost of carrying costs and ordering costs.
